## Quantum Walks on the Integer Lattice

We now precisely describe quantum walks on ${\mathbb Z}$. A *quantum walk* is described by a unitary operator on the Hilbert space $\mathcal{H} = \ell^2({\mathbb Z}) \otimes {\mathbb C}^2$, which models a state space in which a wave packet comes equipped with a “spin” at each integer site. Here, the elementary tensors of the form $\delta_n \otimes e_\uparrow$, and $\delta_n \otimes e_\downarrow$ with $n \in {\mathbb Z}$ comprise an orthonormal basis of ${\mathcal H}$ (where $\{e_\uparrow,e_\downarrow\}$ denotes the canonical basis of ${\mathbb C}^2$). A time-homogeneous quantum walk scenario is given as soon as coins $$\label{e.timehomocoins}
C_{n}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
c^{11}_{n} & c^{12}_{n} \\
c^{21}_{n} & c^{22}_{n}
\end{pmatrix}
\in {\mathbb U}(2), \quad n \in {\mathbb Z},$$ are specified. As one passes from time $t$ to time $t+1$, the update rule of the quantum walk applies the coins coordinatewise and shifts spin-up states to the right and spin-down states the the left, viz. $$\begin{aligned}
\delta_{n} \otimes e_\uparrow & \mapsto
  c^{11}_{n} \delta_{n+1} \otimes e_\uparrow
+ c^{21}_{n} \delta_{n-1} \otimes e_\downarrow , \label{e.updaterule1} \\
\delta_n \otimes e_\downarrow  & \mapsto
  c^{12}_{n} \delta_{n+1} \otimes e_\uparrow
+ c^{22}_{n} \delta_{n-1} \otimes e_\downarrow \label{e.updaterule2}.
\end{aligned}$$ If we extend this by linearity and continuity to general elements of $\mathcal{H}$, this defines a unitary operator $U$ on $\mathcal{H}$. Equivalently, denote a typical element $\psi \in {\mathcal H}$ by $$\label{eq:typicalelt}
\psi
=
\sum_{n \in {\mathbb Z}} \left( \psi_{\uparrow,n} \delta_n \otimes e_\uparrow + \psi_{\downarrow,n} \delta_n \otimes e_\downarrow \right),$$ where one must have $$\sum_{n \in {\mathbb Z}}\left( \left| \psi_{\uparrow,n} \right|^2 + \left| \psi_{\downarrow,n} \right|^2 \right)
<
\infty.$$ We may then describe the action of $U$ in coordinates via $$\label{eq:ucoord:def}
\begin{split}
[U\psi]_{\uparrow,n}
& =
c_{n-1}^{11} \psi_{\uparrow,n-1} + c_{n-1}^{12} \psi_{\downarrow,n-1}, \\
[U\psi]_{\downarrow,n}
& =
c_{n+1}^{21} \psi_{\uparrow,n+1} + c_{n+1}^{22} \psi_{\downarrow,n+1}.
\end{split}$$ Next, order the basis of $\mathcal{H}$ by setting $\varphi_{2m} = \delta_m \otimes e_\uparrow$, $\varphi_{2m+1} = \delta_m \otimes e_\downarrow$ for $m \in {\mathbb Z}$

Now by taking any sequence $k_n \in {\mathbb Z}$ such that $\lim_{n\to\infty}\|k_n\beta\|_{{\mathbb R}/{\mathbb Z}}=0$, passing to the Hilbert-Schmidt norm, and using <a href="#L2norm:estimate" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="L2norm:estimate">[L2norm:estimate]</a>, one readily checks that $$\label{eq:L1:liminf0}
\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\int_{\mathbb T}\|B(x+k_n\beta)-B(x)\|^2 \, dx
=
0.$$ In particular, one may take $k_n=4q_n$, where $q_n$ is the denominator of the continued fraction approximants of $\beta$. Hence, <a href="#trace:estimate" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="trace:estimate">[trace:estimate]</a> and <a href="#eq:L1:liminf0" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:L1:liminf0">[eq:L1:liminf0]</a> imply that $$\label{eq:traceL1decay}
\lim_{n \to \infty} \| \Phi_{4q_n} \|_{L^1}
=
0.$$ Now, we will use $N$, defined by <a href="#eq:tmNdef" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:tmNdef">[eq:tmNdef]</a>. Evidently, we can rewrite $N$ as follows: $$\begin{aligned}
\label{trace:extremalcoefficient}
N(x)
& =
\begin{pmatrix}-2iz^{-1} & e^{2\pi i x}-e^{-2\pi i x}\\ e^{2\pi i x}-e^{-2\pi i x} & -2iz
\end{pmatrix},\quad
x \in {\mathbb T}, \; z \in {\mathbb C}\setminus \{0\}..
\end{aligned}$$ A direct computation shows that $$\label{trouble}
\Phi_k(x)=\mathrm{tr} M_k(x)-2\cos(2\pi k\theta)
=
\frac{\mathrm{tr} N_k(x)}{(-2i)^k}\prod^{k-1}_{j=0}\sec[2\pi (x+j\beta)]-2\cos(2\pi k\theta).$$ Let $$f_k(x)
=
(-2i)^k\prod^{k-1}_{j=0}\cos[2\pi (x+j\beta)],
\quad
k \in {\mathbb Z}_+, \; x \in {\mathbb T}.$$ Then, <a href="#trouble" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="trouble">[trouble]</a> gives $$\label{trouble2}
f_k(x)\Phi_k(x)=\mathrm{tr} N_k(x)-2\cos(2\pi k\theta)f_k(x),
\text{ for all } k \in {\mathbb Z}_+, \; x \in {\mathbb T}.$$ First, by a straightforward computation, we notice that $\mathrm{tr} (N_k(x))$ is a trigonometric polynomial of the form $$\mathrm{tr} (N_k(x))
=
\sum^{k}_{j=-k}c_n e^{2\pi ijx}.$$ For $k \in 2{\mathbb Z}_+$, one readily checks that the extremal Fourier coefficient is given by $$c_k=2e^{\pi ik(k-1)\beta}.$$ It is clear that $f_k(x)$ is trigonometric polynomial of degree $k$ as well. Moreover, the extremal Fourier coefficient of $f_k(x)$ is $e^{\pi ik(k-1)\beta}$ whenever $k\in 4{\mathbb Z}_+$. Hence, for any $k \in 4{\mathbb Z}_+$, we obtain for the right hand side of <a href="#trouble2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="trouble2">[trouble2]</a>: $$\begin{aligned}
\|\mathrm{tr} N_k - 2\cos(2\pi k\theta)f_k\|_{L^1}
& \ge
\left|\int_{\mathbb T}\left(\mathrm{tr} N_k(x)-2\cos(2\pi k\theta)f_k(x)\right)e^{-2\pi ikx} \, dx\right|\\
&=
\left|2e^{\pi ik(k-1)\beta}- 2\cos(2\pi k\theta)e^{\pi ik(k-1)\beta}\right|\\
&=
2-2\cos(2\pi k\theta).
\end{aligned}$$ Now, since $\theta\not\in E(\mathbf k)$ where $\mathbf k=\{4q_{n_l}\}^\infty_{l=1}$, we may choose $m\in{\mathbb Z}_+$ and a subsequence $(k_s)_{s\in{\mathbb Z}_+}$ of $(4q_{n_l})$ such that $$\left\|k_s\theta\right\|_{{\mathbb R}/{\mathbb Z}}>\frac1{4m}.$$ Let $c = 2-2\cos(\frac1{4m})>0$. Then for each $s\in{\mathbb Z}_+$, it holds that $$\label{right:estimate}
\| f_{k_s} \Phi_{k_s} \|_{L^1}
=
\|\mathrm{tr} N_{k_s}-2\cos(2\pi k_s\theta)f_{k_s}\|_{L^1}
\ge
2-2\cos(2\pi k_s\theta)
>
c
>
0.$$

On the other hand, since $(k_s)$ is a subsequence of $(4q_{n_l})$, <a href="#eq:traceL1decay" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:traceL1decay">[eq:traceL1decay]</a>, and <a href="#eq:subharmonic:prod2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:subharmonic:prod2">[eq:subharmonic:prod2]</a> with $r=4$ imply the following for the right-hand side of <a href="#trouble2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="trouble2">[trouble2]</a>: $$\label{left:estimate}
\lim_{s\rightarrow\infty}\|f_{k_s}\Phi_{k_s}\|_{L^1}
\le
C_0^4\lim_{s\rightarrow\infty}\|\Phi_{k_s}\|_{L^1}
=
0.$$ So <a href="#right:estimate" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="right:estimate">[right:estimate]</a> and <a href="#left:estimate" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="left:estimate">[left:estimate]</a> together implies $0 < c \leq 0$, a contradiction. ◻

