Let $f,g$ be continuous functions from $X$ to $i\mathrm{SU}(2)$ (i.e., $\mathrm{U}(2)$ matrices with determinant $-1$). Note that elements of $i\mathrm{SU}(2)$ can be written in the form $$\label{eq:iSU2}
\begin{pmatrix}
\overline \alpha & \rho\\
\overline \rho & -\alpha
\end{pmatrix},$$ where $\alpha\in \overline{{\mathbb D}}$ and $|\rho|^2+|\alpha|^2 = 1$. Notice in particular that $\rho$ may be a complex number.

Let us write the matrix elements of $f$ and $g$ as $$f(x)
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\overline {\alpha_f(x)} & \rho_f(x)\\
\overline {\rho_f(x)} & -\alpha_f(x)
\end{pmatrix},
\quad
\text{and}
\quad
g(x)
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\overline {\alpha_g(x)} & \rho_g(x)\\
\overline {\rho_g(x)} & -\alpha_g(x)
\end{pmatrix},
\quad
x \in X.$$ For each $x \in X$, we will define a CMV operator $\mathcal E_x$ by $\mathcal E_x = \mathcal L_x\mathcal M_x$, where $$\begin{pmatrix}
(\mathcal L_x)_{2k-1,2k-1} & (\mathcal L_x)_{2k-1,2k}\\
(\mathcal L_x)_{2k,2k-1} & (\mathcal L_x)_{2k,2k}
\end{pmatrix}=f(T^kx),\ k\in{\mathbb Z}$$ and $$\begin{pmatrix}
(\mathcal M_x)_{2k-2,2k-2} & (\mathcal M_x)_{2k-2,2k-1}\\
(\mathcal M_x)_{2k-1,2k-2} & (\mathcal M_x)_{2k-1,2k-1}
\end{pmatrix}=g(T^kx), \ k\in {\mathbb Z},$$ and all other entries of $\mathcal L$ and $\mathcal M$ are zero. Compare ; here we essentially set $\alpha_g(x)=-\overline{\alpha_{-1}}$ and $\alpha_f(x)=-\overline{\alpha_{0}}$. We then assume the integrability condition $$\label{eq:logrhoL1}
-\int_X \log| \rho_f | \, d\mu
-\int_X \log| \rho_g | \, d\mu
<
\infty,$$ which is the appropriate translation of the condition <a href="#integrability:cocycle" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="integrability:cocycle">[integrability:cocycle]</a> to the present context.

Let us write the matrix elements of $f$ and $g$ as $$f(x)
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\overline {\alpha_f(x)} & \rho_f(x)\\
\overline {\rho_f(x)} & -\alpha_f(x)
\end{pmatrix},
\quad
\text{and}
\quad
g(x)
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\overline {\alpha_g(x)} & \rho_g(x)\\
\overline {\rho_g(x)} & -\alpha_g(x)
\end{pmatrix},
\quad
x \in X.$$ For each $x \in X$, we will define a CMV operator $\mathcal E_x$ by $\mathcal E_x = \mathcal L_x\mathcal M_x$, where $$\begin{pmatrix}
(\mathcal L_x)_{2k-1,2k-1} & (\mathcal L_x)_{2k-1,2k}\\
(\mathcal L_x)_{2k,2k-1} & (\mathcal L_x)_{2k,2k}
\end{pmatrix}=f(T^kx),\ k\in{\mathbb Z}$$ and $$\begin{pmatrix}
(\mathcal M_x)_{2k-2,2k-2} & (\mathcal M_x)_{2k-2,2k-1}\\
(\mathcal M_x)_{2k-1,2k-2} & (\mathcal M_x)_{2k-1,2k-1}
\end{pmatrix}=g(T^kx), \ k\in {\mathbb Z},$$ and all other entries of $\mathcal L$ and $\mathcal M$ are zero. Compare ; here we essentially set $\alpha_g(x)=-\overline{\alpha_{-1}}$ and $\alpha_f(x)=-\overline{\alpha_{0}}$. We then assume the integrability condition $$\label{eq:logrhoL1}
-\int_X \log| \rho_f | \, d\mu
-\int_X \log| \rho_g | \, d\mu
<
\infty,$$ which is the appropriate translation of the condition <a href="#integrability:cocycle" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="integrability:cocycle">[integrability:cocycle]</a> to the present context.

We shall use modified Gesztesy-Zinchenko (GZ) transfer matrices, normalized so the $\rho$ term disappears: $$\label{eq:gzmatdef}
A^z_f(x)
=
\begin{pmatrix}
-\alpha_f(x)& 1\\
1& -\overline{\alpha_f(x)}
\end{pmatrix},\quad
A^z_g(x)
=
\begin{pmatrix}
-\overline{\alpha_g(x)}& z\\
1/z& -\alpha_g(x)
\end{pmatrix}.$$ By GZ cocycle recursion, if $x\in X_0$, then $u_x=(u_{x}(n))_{n\in{\mathbb Z}}$ and $v_x=(v_{x}(n))_{n\in{\mathbb Z}}\in {\mathbb C}^{\mathbb Z}$ solve the equations $\mathcal E_x u_x=zu_x$ and $\mathcal M_x u_x=zv_x$ (note that these two equations also imply $\mathcal E^\top_x v_x=zv_x$) if and only if: $$\begin{aligned}
\label{GZrecursionOdd}
&\begin{pmatrix}
u_x(k)\\
v_x(k)
\end{pmatrix}=
\frac{1}{\rho_{g}(T^{\frac{k+1}2}(x))}A_g(T^{\frac{k+1}2}x)\begin{pmatrix}
u_x(k-1)\\
v_x(k-1)
\end{pmatrix}
, \text{$k$ odd.}\\
\label{GZrecursionEven}
&\begin{pmatrix}
u_x(k)\\
v_x(k)
\end{pmatrix}=
\frac{1}{\rho_f(T^{\frac k2}x)}A_f(T^{\frac k2}x)\begin{pmatrix}
u_x(k-1)\\
v_x(k-1)
\end{pmatrix}
, \text{$k$ even,}
\end{aligned}$$

Recall that $T$ is a homeomorphism on a compact metric space $X$. Assume from now on that $T$ satisfies the following additional properties:

1.  $T$ is strictly ergodic, i.e., $T$ is minimal and uniquely ergodic, and let $\mu$ be the unique invariant measure.

2.  ${\mathrm{supp}}(\mu) = X$, i.e., $\mu(Y)>0$ for each open set $Y\subset X$.

3.  $T$ is an isometry, i.e. $d(Tx,Ty)=d(x,y)$ for all $x$, $y\in X$, where $d$ is the metric on $X$.

## Dominated splitting away from the spectrum

In this section, we prove the relation $\Sigma \supset\{z\in\partial{\mathbb D}:(T,A^z_fA^z_g)\notin\mathcal D\mathcal S\}$. In fact, we prove a slightly stronger result: $$\label{eq:DSawayspectrum}
{\mathbb C}\setminus (\Sigma\cup\{0\}) \subset \{z\in{\mathbb C}:(T,A^z_fA^z_g) \in \mathcal D\mathcal S\}.$$ In other words, for spectral parameters away from the spectrum of the operators $\mathcal E_x$, the dynamical system $(T,A^z_fA^z_g)$ admits a dominated splitting. We will begin by defining the Carathéodory and Schur functions. It will turn out that the dominating sections will (very nearly) be given by the Schur and anti-Schur functions. The key idea here is to relate Schur functions to Weyl solutions to the difference equation and then use Combes-Thomas type estimates on the solutions to get domination. The details follow.

Notice that ${\mathcal E}_x$ becomes a direct sum of two half line operators if $\alpha_*(T^mx)\in\partial{\mathbb D}$ for $*=f$ or $g$ and for some $m\in{\mathbb Z}$. Then for all $(x,s)\in X\times[0,2\pi)$, we define the half line unitary operators ${\mathcal E}^{(s)}_{x,j,+}$ on $\ell^2[j,+\infty)$ and ${\mathcal E}^{(s)}_{x,j,-}$ on $\ell^2(-\infty,j]$ via the following formula: $$\ \mathcal E_x=
\begin{cases}
\mathcal E^{(s)}_{x,2m-2,-}\oplus \mathcal E^{(s)}_{x,2m-1,+}, &\mbox{ if }\alpha_g(T^mx)=-e^{-is}\in\partial {\mathbb D},\\
\mathcal E^{(s)}_{x,2m-1,-}\oplus \mathcal E^{(s)}_{x,2m,+}, &\mbox{ if }\alpha_f(T^mx)=-e^{-is}\in\partial {\mathbb D}.
\end{cases}$$ Let $\mu^{(s)}_{g,x,-}$ be the spectral measures corresponding to $\mathcal E^{(s)}_{x,-2,-}$, $\mu^{(s)}_{g,x,+}$ to $\mathcal E^{(s)}_{x,-1,+}$, $\mu^{(s)}_{f,x,-}$ to $\mathcal E^{(s)}_{x,-1,-}$, and $\mu^{(s)}_{f,x,+}$ to $\mathcal E^{(s)}_{x,0,+}$.

Notice in any case, ${\mathcal E}_x$ and $\mathcal E^{(s)}_{x,-j,-}\oplus \mathcal E^{(s)}_{x,-j+1,+}$ differ by a finite rank operator. Since finite rank perturbations preserve essential spectrum, we obtain for all $z\notin \Sigma$, either $z$ is in the resolvent set of ${\mathcal E}^{(s)}_{x,j,\pm}$, or it is in the discrete spectrum of ${\mathcal E}^{(s)}_{x,j,\pm}$. Let ${\mathbb C}{\mathbb P}^1={\mathbb C}\cup\{\infty\}$ denote the Riemann sphere. We may then define for $*=f$ or $g$ a pair of one-parameter families of functions $m^{(s)}_{*,\pm}:X\times({\mathbb C}\setminus(\Sigma\cup\{0\})\rightarrow{\mathbb C}{\mathbb P}^1$ as follows: $$\begin{aligned}
m^{(s)}_{*,-}(x,z)=-\oint_{\partial\mathbb D}\frac{\zeta+z}{\zeta-z}d\mu^{(s)}_{*,x,-}(\zeta) \label{M_-}
\end{aligned}$$ and $$\begin{aligned}
m^{(s)}_{*,+}(x,z)=\frac{\mathrm{Re}(1-\alpha_*(x))-i\mathrm{Im}(\alpha_*(x))\oint_{\partial\mathbb D}\frac{\zeta+z}{\zeta-z}d\mu^{(s)}_{*,x,+}(\zeta)}{-i\mathrm{Im}(\alpha_*(x))+\mathrm{Re}(1+\alpha_*(x))\oint_{\partial\mathbb D}\frac{\zeta+z}{\zeta-z}d\mu^{(s)}_{*,x,+}(\zeta)},\label{M_+}
\end{aligned}$$ where e.g. $m^{(s)}_{g,-}(x,z)\in {\mathbb C}$ if $z$ is in the resolvent set of ${\mathcal E}^{(s)}_{x,-2,-}$, and $m^{(s)}_{g,-}(x,z)=\infty$ if $z$ is in the discrete spectrum of ${\mathcal E}^{(s)}_{x,-2,-}$.

Then we define functions $\Phi^{(s)}_{*,\pm}(x,z):X\times({\mathbb C}\setminus(\Sigma\cup\{0\})\rightarrow{\mathbb C}{\mathbb P}^1$ by $$\label{eq.mtoM}
\Phi^{(s)}_{*,\pm}(x,z)=\frac{1-m^{(s)}_{*,\pm}(x,z)}{1+m^{(s)}_{*,\pm}(x,z)}.$$

The Schur and Caratheodory functions play an important role in the spectral theory of unitary operators, as their limiting behavior on the unit circle gives us information about the spectral measures. For instance, $\Phi^{(s)}_{g,-}(x,z)=-1$ for some $z\in\partial{\mathbb D}$ if and only if $z$ is a pole of $m^{(s)}_{g,-}(x,z)$, which happens if and only if the spectral measure $\mu^{(s)}_{g,x,-}$ has a pure point at $z$, i.e. $z$ is an eigenvalue of ${\mathcal E}^{(s)}_{x,-2,-}$.

Note that if $x\in X_0$ and $z\notin \Sigma\cup\{0\}$, then $\mathcal E_xu=zu$ and $\mathcal M_x u_x = z v_x$ admit solutions $u_{x,\pm}, v_{x,\pm}$ which are square-summable at $\pm\infty$. In other words, $u_{x,\pm},v_{x,\pm} \in \ell^2({\mathbb Z}_\pm)$. We define the following: $$\label{eq:mfct:solns-odd}
\Phi_{\pm,x,z}(k)
:=
\frac{v_{x,\pm}(k)}{u_{x,\pm}(k)}, \text{ $k$ odd,}$$ $$\label{eq:mfct:solns-even}
\Phi_{\pm,x,z}(k)
:=
\frac{u_{x,\pm}(k)}{zv_{x,\pm}(k)}, \text{ $k$ even.}$$ Note however that our $u_x$ and $v_x$ come from rather than from , which is why our $\Phi$ functions are defined differently from .

Next, we define the following functions by fixing a particular choice of $k\in{\mathbb Z}$: $$\label{eq:mfct:solns}
\Phi_{g,\pm}(x,z):=\Phi_{\pm,x,z}(-2),\ \Phi_{f,\pm}(x,z):=\Phi_{\pm,x,z}(-1).$$ Then, we have $$\label{eq:mfct:solns.alternative}
e^{-is}\Phi^{(s)}_{*,\pm}(x,z)=\Phi_{*,\pm}(x,z),\ *=f,g$$

This comes from modifying the calculations in . For simplicity, Gesztesy and Zinchenko always assume that the singular Verblunsky coefficients take on the value $\alpha_g(x)=-1$ to get $\mathcal E_x=\mathcal E^{(0)}_{x,-2,-}\oplus \mathcal E^{(0)}_{x,-1,+}$, (and similarly with $\alpha_f(x)=-1$) but if we dispense with that assumption and allow $\alpha_*(x)=-e^{-is}\in\partial{\mathbb D}$ instead, then this results in factors of $e^{is}$ replacing the $1$ in their (2.51) and (2.54), which leads to the $e^{is}$ factors in their (2.57) and (2.58). Notice however that the relation <a href="#eq:mfct:solns.alternative" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:mfct:solns.alternative">[eq:mfct:solns.alternative]</a> only holds for $x\in X_0$.

Let us first assume $\lvert\alpha_g(x)\rvert=1$. Regardless whether $\lvert \alpha_f(x)\rvert<1$ or $\lvert \alpha_f(x)\rvert=1$, we can then calculate that $$\ker(A^z_f(x)A^z_g(x)) =\binom{\alpha_g(z)+z\alpha_f(x)}{\alpha_f(x)\overline{\alpha_g(x)}+z^{-1}}=\binom{z}{\overline{\alpha_g(x)}} =\ker(A^z_g(x)).$$

We first show that $(z\Phi_{-}(x,z),1)^\top \notin \mathrm{ker} (A_g^z(x))$. Since $A_f A_g$ is not the zero matrix, we have $$\mathrm{ker}
(A_f^z(x)A_g^z(x))
=
\mathrm{ker}(A_g^z(x))=
\mathrm{span}\begin{pmatrix}
z\alpha_g(x)\\
1
\end{pmatrix}$$ by a straightforward dimension-counting argument. Let $\alpha_g=-e^{-is}$. Notice that by <a href="#eq:mfct:solns.alternative" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:mfct:solns.alternative">[eq:mfct:solns.alternative]</a> $\Phi_{g,-}(x,z)=-\alpha_g(x)\Phi^{(s)}_{g,-}(x,z)$. Hence $$\label{transversal:to:kernel}
\binom{z\Phi_{g,-}(x,z)}{1}=\begin{pmatrix}
z\alpha_g(x)\\
1
\end{pmatrix}
\iff
\Phi^{(s)}_{g,-}(x,z)=-1.$$ By <a href="#eq.mtoM" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq.mtoM">[eq.mtoM]</a>, $\Phi^{(s)}_{g,-}(x,z)=-1$ implies $m^{(s)}_{g,-}(x,z)=\infty$, which in turn implies that $d\mu^{(s)}_{x,-}$ has a pure point at $z$. Since $\mathcal E_x=\mathcal E^{(s)}_{x,-2,-}\oplus \mathcal E^{(s)}_{x,-1,+}$, this implies that $z$ is an eigenvalue of $\mathcal E_x$, contrary to our assumption that $z \notin \Sigma$.

The calculations proceed in a similar way for the case $\lvert \alpha_f(x)\rvert=1$, $\lvert\alpha_g(x)\rvert<1$. In this case, we have that $A^z_f(x)$ is singular but $A_g^z(x)$ is not. Thus the kernel of $A_f^z(x)A_g^z(x)$ is $$(A_g^z(x))^{-1}\mathrm{ker}(A_f^z(x))=
\mathrm{span}\left\{A_g^z(x)^{-1}\begin{pmatrix}
1\\
\alpha_f(x)
\end{pmatrix}\right\}.\label{fkernel}$$

We let $E^+(.,z)$ be the continuous lift of $z\Phi_{g,-}(.,z)$ and let $E^-(.,z)$ be a continuous lift of $z \Phi_{g,+}(.,z)$ to subspaces of $\mathbb C^2$. By Lemma <a href="#Jointlycontinuous" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Jointlycontinuous">20</a>, formula <a href="#transport-" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="transport-">[transport-]</a>, Lemma <a href="#l:m_function_invariance" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="l:m_function_invariance">21</a> and <a href="#l:unif:trans" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="l:unif:trans">22</a>, we obtain all $x\in X$, it holds that $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:inv:E-}&A^z(x)E^-(x,z)\subseteq E^-(Tx,z),\\
\label{eq:inv:E+}&A^z(x)E^+(x,z)= E^+(Tx,z).
\end{aligned}$$

Then we define $Q^z(x)$ to be: $$\begin{pmatrix}z & z\Phi_{g,+}(x,z)\\ \frac{1}{\Phi_{g,-}(x,z)} &1\end{pmatrix},\ z\in{\mathbb D};\mbox{ or }
\begin{pmatrix}z\Phi_{g,-}(x,z) & z\\ 1& \frac{1}{\Phi_{g,+}(x,z)}\end{pmatrix},\ z\notin{\mathbb D}.$$

Then since $\Phi_{g,+}$ is a Schur function and $\Phi_{g,-}$ is an anti-Schur function, we have $$Q^z\in C(X,\mathrm{M}_2({\mathbb C})).$$ Next we show $Q^z(x)$ is nonsingular for all $z\in {\mathbb C}\setminus(\Sigma\cup\{0\})$ and all $x\in X$. Indeed, if $z\in{\mathbb D}$, then Lemma <a href="#l:unif:trans" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="l:unif:trans">22</a> implies $$|\det(Q^z(x))|=\frac1{|\Phi_{g,-}(x,z)|}|z\Phi_{g,-}(x,z)-z\Phi_{g,+}(x,z)|\neq 0$$ for all $x\in X$ whenever $\Phi_{g,-}(x,z)\neq\infty$. But $\Phi_{g,-}(x,z)=\infty$ implies $\det(Q^z(x))=|z|\neq 0$ since we assumed $z\neq 0$. If $z\notin{\mathbb D}$, then by <a href="#eq:unif:trans2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:unif:trans2">[eq:unif:trans2]</a>, $$|\det(Q^z(x))|=\frac{1}{|\Phi_{g,+}(x,z)|}|z\Phi_{g,-}(x,z)-z\Phi_{g,+}(x,z)|>\mathrm{dist}(z,\Sigma)>0.$$ In any case, we obtain $$\label{eq:GL:conjugacy}
Q^z\in C(X,\mathrm{GL}(2,{\mathbb C})).$$

